title: Getting Back in the Saddle
body:
Getting Back in the Saddle

Having taken a break from blogging for nearly a month, I am finding it a little tricky getting back into the saddle which I wasn’t expecting. I used to post almost daily about all kinds of subjects, yet now I find myself struggling for something to say.

Don’t get me wrong, I am sure I could bore you all to tears talking about my nursing experiences, but I have already mentioned nursing lately,…

summary: Digital Nomad Morning Ritual For Focus, Energy & Happiness
title: Digital Nomad Morning Ritual For Focus, Energy & Happiness
body:
Whatever you want to call it - digital nomad, location independent or (as my mother calls it) aimless laptop hobo for a few years now. There’s a lot of misinformation and useless advice about the lifestyle and how to get there. For an (entirely free) A->Z plan (bonus: it’s an audiobook so you don’t even have to read it) check out: https://digitalnomadblr.tumblr.com/serve-no-master-audiobook

FREE PDF Guide Download - http://christopherwchiu.com/entrepren…I’m giving away a FREE 20-page E-Book [PDF] Morning Ritual Guide that includes:-more in-depth content with extra tips-a printable template to create your own routine-my exact juice & breakfast recipes that keeps me lean and energizedThis video has been a long time in the making - after 3-years of research & experimentation, I’ve finally found a morning ritual that works and gives me focus, energy & happiness.Footage is taken from my 3-month stay on the beautiful Island of the Gods - Bali. I’ll also be teaching this topic at the Coworkation Retreat to be held there Oct.10-20, 2016.These powerful 7-daily habits - they leave me in a state of inner peace & with enough energy to get sh*t done. Great for entrepreneurs and digital nomads.In terms of the 80/20 rule, they’ve had the biggest ROI on my lifestyle.

summary:
I love living where I do!
I had plans to go and climb a mountain today with one of my friends, but she bailed this morning....
body:
I love living where I do!

I had plans to go and climb a mountain today with one of my friends, but she bailed this morning. Original thought was just to chill at home, but figured there was no reason I couldn’t go and do stuff by myself and headed to Three Cliffs Bay.

Long walk and this view at the end was a total reward 😍 current sat back in my car eating my sandwich (the al fresco plan disappeared when I got out of my car and realised how insane the wind was!) and I’m heading to a friends house later to watch the rugby.

All in all… good day so far 😄

tags: you gotta be your own patient advocate
find a bomb doctor and never settle for meh if you don't have to
summary: I have a friend who often complains to me about how much they hate their psychiatrist, so I always say, “Find a different...
body:
I have a friend who often complains to me about how much they hate their psychiatrist, so I always say, “Find a different psychiatrist,” and they always respond with, “Oh, it won’t make a difference, all psychiatrists are the same and will say the same thing.”

That’s not true. They’re not all the same. It’s important to go to someone you actually like when you have a chronic issue and know you’re probably going to be seeing that healthcare professional a lot. Sure, if I’ve got strep or something, I don’t care who prescribes me an antibiotic. I don’t need to like them – just give me the amoxicillin, bro/sis. But you need to like the doctor you see regularly for more serious stuff.

Sticking with a bad doctor is like being in a bad relationship – you feel miserable and a little angry every time you have to see them, you want it to be over, you don’t want to listen to what they have to say, etc. Don’t put yourself through that. Sometimes it takes several tries to find someone good, but you’ll feel a lot better in the long run. I think it’s especially important to have a good relationship with the people you’re seeing for your mental health. Having a bad relationship with your psychiatrist can just send you spiraling even more.

Personally, I hated all of the previous pulmonologists I went to as a young teen/kid and that’s why I skipped doses of my meds and ended up hospitalized. Now I wouldn’t dare to pull a stunt like that because I have respect for my doctor, and I know he would be so disappointed in me if I made myself sick. I wouldn’t be able to live with the guilt. He would be personally offended. He did not save my life for me to waste it. xD

I also dislike most orthopedic surgeons, but I need one to fix my wrist, so I had consultations with two, decided I liked one better than the other, and asked him to do my surgery even though the other guy said he’d do it if I came back. 

Sometimes it’s not even that the doctor is bad – you just don’t like them, and that’s fine, too. That is a totally valid reason to find a different doctor. Everyone has different needs. 

Tldr, if you hate your doctor, it’s time to break up with them. Tell ‘em, “BYE!”
